# Hands - on Labs - Day 2

# Design, Extend, Ground, and Orchestrate Scalable AI Agents with Microsoft Foundry and Agent Framework

## Overall Estimated Duration: 8 Hours

## Overview

In this hands-on workshop, you will design, build, extend, and orchestrate scalable enterprise AI agents using **Microsoft Foundry** and the **Microsoft Agent Framework**. Starting from a single AI agent grounded in enterprise knowledge through **Azure AI Search**, you will progress to multi-agent systems that collaborate via **Agent-to-Agent (A2A)** communication, extend them with external tools and data through the **Model Context Protocol (MCP)**, and deploy them as persistent, cloud-hosted solutions in the **Microsoft Foundry Agent Service**.

You will then apply these skills to a real-world scenario: an AI-powered **customer resolution agent** for Contoso Electronics. By combining **Work IQ (email)**, **Foundry IQ (policies)**, and **Fabric IQ (data)** in a single Foundry Agent, you will deliver a Copilot-like experience that analyzes customer issues, validates facts across systems, applies business policies, and generates professional resolutions.

## Objectives

By the end of this workshop, participants will be able to:

- **Set up an AI project and run chat completion from VS Code:** Create a Microsoft Foundry project, deploy GPT-4 and embedding models, and validate secure connectivity from Visual Studio Code.

- **Build a single-purpose AI agent:** Develop a Health Insurance Plans Analyzer that interprets benefit data and generates comparative visualizations through code execution.

- **Develop a multi-agent collaborative system:** Orchestrate specialized Search, Report, and Validation agents that collaborate via Agent-to-Agent (A2A) communication to produce grounded analytical reports.

- **Ground agents in enterprise knowledge:** Configure Azure AI Search and Azure Storage to index policy documents, then build a Foundry Agent that acts as a support and operations assistant.

- **Model business data in Microsoft Fabric:** Create a Fabric workspace, lakehouse, and ontology defining entities and relationships across customers, orders, tickets, and refunds, surfaced through a Fabric Data Agent.

- **Deliver a unified customer resolution agent:** Integrate Work IQ (email), Foundry IQ (policies), and Fabric IQ (data) into one agent that analyzes issues, validates facts, applies policies, and generates professional responses.

## Pre-requisites

Participants should have:

- **Azure & cloud experience** – Familiarity with the Azure Portal, Resource Groups, virtual machines, Azure Storage, and Azure AI services.

- **Programming skills** – Basic Python knowledge (async/await, environment variables, and API calls).

- **AI concepts** – Understanding of LLMs, embeddings, ontologies, Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG), and prompt engineering.

- **Development tools** – Proficiency with Visual Studio Code, terminal usage, and Git.

- **Agent Framework awareness** – Basic knowledge of agent architectures, tools, and orchestration patterns.

- **Microsoft Fabric basics** – Familiarity with workspace and lakehouse concepts, along with data modeling and entity-relationship concepts.

- **Security & integration** – Knowledge of Azure role-based access control (RBAC) and authentication methods, and a general awareness of how AI services integrate with data platforms and enterprise email/communication workflows for intelligent decision-making.

## Architecture

The workflow begins in the **Microsoft Foundry** portal, where you create an AI project, deploy GPT-4 and embedding models, and ground agents by ingesting enterprise documents from **Azure Storage** into an **Azure AI Search** index for Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG). Using the **Microsoft Agent Framework** SDK, agents evolve from single-turn responders into persistent, cloud-hosted services in the **Microsoft Foundry Agent Service**, where a Planner and domain Worker agents collaborate through **A2A** communication and connect to external tools via the **Model Context Protocol (MCP)**.

The solution then extends into a unified customer-resolution system. **Microsoft Fabric** supplies a lakehouse and ontology model, surfaced through a Fabric Data Agent, and three intelligence layers converge in a single Foundry Agent — **Work IQ** analyzes emails, **Fabric IQ** validates facts against business data, and **Foundry IQ** applies policy and SLA guidance — producing accurate, policy-compliant recommendations.

## Explanation of Components

The architecture for this workshop involves the following key components:

1. **Microsoft Foundry:** A cloud platform and central hub for developing, deploying, and managing enterprise AI agents. It provides a managed Agent Service runtime, centralized project management, and Application Insights monitoring, and hosts the **Foundry Agent** that orchestrates customer-resolution workflows while integrating multiple IQ tools (Work IQ, Foundry IQ, Fabric IQ) into a unified interface.

1. **Microsoft Agent Framework SDK:** The official Python SDK for building intelligent, modular agents that replaces AutoGen and Semantic Kernel. It features native Agent-to-Agent (A2A) communication, Model Context Protocol integration, and Microsoft Foundry support, enabling production-ready enterprise agent systems with standardized tool usage.

1. **Azure AI Search:** A vector-based, cloud search engine that powers Retrieval-Augmented Generation. It provides hybrid retrieval (vector similarity + keyword search), semantic ranking for improved relevance, and document indexing, ensuring agents deliver grounded, factually accurate responses from enterprise knowledge sources such as policy documents.

1. **Azure OpenAI:** An enterprise-grade service providing access to advanced LLMs through secure API endpoints, offering chat completion, embedding models, content filtering, and compliance features. It integrates seamlessly with Microsoft Foundry, enabling agents to leverage GPT-4 while maintaining data privacy and governance.

1. **Model Context Protocol (MCP):** A standardized interface enabling agents to access external knowledge and tools securely. MCP connects enterprise data sources, external APIs like Freshdesk, and custom tools with structured schemas, ensuring reliable, auditable interactions and forming the foundation for extensible enterprise AI systems.

1. **Microsoft Fabric:** A unified analytics platform for data engineering and data science. Its **Lakehouse** stores business data (customers, orders, shipments, support tickets, refunds); its **Ontology (Preview)** defines entity types (Customer, Order, OrderItem, SupportTicket, RefundClaim, ShipmentTrackingEvent) and relationships (Places, Contains, hasSupportTicket, hasTrackingEvent, mayLeadTo); and its **Fabric Data Agent** interprets business data to answer questions about orders, shipments, refunds, and inventory.

1. **Work IQ (Email Integration):** Provides email analysis and context extraction, allowing the agent to review customer and internal communications and extract key information about issues, complaints, and urgency.

1. **Foundry IQ (Policy Knowledge):** A knowledge base connected to policy documents in Azure Storage, enabling the agent to apply business rules, SLA guidance, escalation criteria, and communication standards for consistent, policy-compliant decision-making.

1. **Fabric IQ (Data Intelligence):** An ontology-based data interpretation layer that provides business-context-aware responses by understanding entity relationships, enabling the agent to validate customer facts, order details, inventory status, and shipment history.

